John Edward: Language skills that are important for the world's citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a track record of academic excellence, and this continued into 2018 with the help of another body of excellent exam results, which were only strengthened by individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to its students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, in their chosen career and place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that designs and implements the appropriate school curriculum, we see modern languages continue to be a popular and preferred topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you talk to a person in a language he understands, it's going to get into his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it will go into his heart."
It's a strong reminder that we shouldn't just rely on the English language when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's exam, we can see that language is at the top of the league tables with the highest passing rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who have studied foreign languages have earned a Higher A grade.
The data, collected from 74 member schools of SCIS, showed that 72 percent of students scored an A grade in Mandarin, while 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners and 63 percent of Spanish learners also scored an A.
It shows that independent schools in Scotland have adopted foreign languages as essential skills that young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages today, as the subject of choice, are considered to be equivalent STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula elsewhere.
In a 2014 survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills, it was found that for reasons given by employers for the difficulty of filling vacant positions, 17 percent were due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are especially needed for young people to be prepared for their future career.
Along with the increase in job opportunities requiring language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of a person's chosen career, if he learns a second language, he will have the advantage in the future due to having a lifelong ability like this.
People who speak multiple languages will automatically gain an advantage because of its ability to communicate directly with people from other countries.
In 2013, according to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent were insufficiently able to speak a foreign language and only French was spoken in a two-digit percentage, which is 15 percent.
This is why it is important for today's youth to invest in language teaching.
Being able to speak many languages, especially in developing economies, will give the youth a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, schools vary greatly when it comes to the languages they teach.
Many schools will focus on more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered most important for the UK when the year 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there is always a language option in independent schools, with specialist teachers in this field.
Independent schools in Scotland are committed to providing an environment suitable for teaching that will prepare young people and give them the skills needed to be successful, regardless of their future.
It is undeniable at this time, in the area of global business, that knowledge of the language remains important for the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
Without a doubt, modern languages should be considered as "powers of global interaction."
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence for Scotland's youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
