North Korea says 'unique' unilateral disarmament
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that its suspicions about the United States are growing because of continued sanctions and that the country will never unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such a situation.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of representatives around the world that North Korea has taken "important measures with good intent" in the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, destroying nuclear test sites, and promising not to develop nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we did not see a corresponding response from the United States," he said.
"While there is no confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and under this situation we will not really unilaterally disarm."
While Ri reiterated North Korea's familiar complaints about Washington's rejection of a "silent" approach to denuclearization that honors North Korea as it takes small steps, his statement appeared important because it did not immediately reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang did then.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the current President of the United States and head of North Korea in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work toward "the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" while Trump pledged to guarantee North Korea's safety.
North Korea has long been seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang should give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also rejected demands to reduce stringent international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States is pressing for denuclearization" and lifting the burden of sanctions to achieve their goals in a violent manner, and they are also protesting against "declaring the end of the war," Ri said.
"The view that sanctions will honour us is a deep dream of people who don't know anything about us.
However, the fact that we're in the middle of a crisis deepens our understanding of the situation."
Ri had no plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which was announced by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister announced three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If South Korea and the United States are not the party to this issue of nuclear disarmament, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula will not lead to a deadlock."
However, the tone of Ri's speech differed greatly from last year, when he told the U.N. General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the U.S. territory with North Korean rockets after "Mr. Evil" Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who threatened last year that he would "really crush" North Korea, hailed Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still much work to be done and sanctions should remain until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no set time for it, and also said, "If it's going to last two years, three years or five months - there's no case."
China and Russia have argued that the U.N. Security Council should honor Pyongyang for its actions.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that: "Security Council sanctions should continue to be enforced strictly and without a minute until we are fully informed of the full, final and confirmed denuclearization."
The Security Council has jointly tightened sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to reduce funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile program.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the U.N. General Assembly and said after he visited Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying there had been progress, only for North Korea to condemn him for making "gangster demands."
North Korea promised in a meeting with Moon this month to demolish a missle site as well as a nuclear complex if the United States took "equal measures."
He said Kim had mentioned to him the "equal measures" he was looking for were security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and a path to the normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students, take a course on having enough rest
This year, a new course at Harvard University is helping its undergraduates get a good night's sleep in an attempt to combat the macho culture of studying overnight while powered by caffeine.
One academic found that students at the world's number one university often don't know about the most basic ways to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, sleep medicine teacher at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believed to be the earliest of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving an issue about the impact of sleep deprivation on the study.
“After that, a woman came up to me and said: ‘Why haven’t I been told this before, in my senior year?’
According to him, no one told him about the value of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
For the first time this year, the course explains to students the importance of having good sleep habits and how they contribute to academic and athletic activities, as well as overall health.
Paul Barreira, psychiatry teacher at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health service, said the university decided to enter the course after learning that students were completely sleep deprived for a week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive activities.
In one section there is a picture of the dorm room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, shoes and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light, and how sleep deprivation affects athleticity, and the importance of a routine for sleep.
In another section, participants were told how sleeplessness increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
There is a campus map, with interactive icons, that encourages participants to reflect on their daily activities.
"We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of the students.
But we believe they have a right to know - as you have a right to know about the health effects of smoking," added Prof Czeisler.
The culture of having an ‘all-nighter' still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students is raising the problem of sleep deprivation.
Making sure you have enough sleep, with good quality, should serve as the students' ‘secret weapon' to fight stress, extreme fatigue and anxiety, he says - also to prevent weight gain, because lack of sleep puts the brain in a state of hunger, so they become constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after taking a class during his first year at Harvard.
He said his eyes were open and he had the inspiration to pursue a school course.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask students to complete a study program like this one before joining a competitive institution.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students should consider setting an alarm when to go to sleep and wake up, and be aware of the adverse effects of ‘blue light' emited by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt circadian rhythms, and cause sleep problems.
