National Trust detects the secret life of bats
New research being conducted outside an estate in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that this will shed light on the behavior of exotic flying mammals and will help guide future conservation activities.
The study will follow scientists at the National Trust for Scotland's common and soprano pipistrelles as well as brown long-eared bats and Daubenton bats at the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to monitor the activities of bats throughout the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Expert sound analysis on all recordings will confirm the frequency of bat calls and which specie makes which sound.
Then, a map of the habitat will be created to allow for a more detailed landscape-scale description of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation adviser for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to find out the benefits of habitat management activities such as the creation of prairies and what is the best way to maintain woodlands for bats and other related species.
The bat population in Scotland and throughout the UK has been significantly reduced over the past century.
They are at risk from construction and development work affecting nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a danger, as well as flypapers and some chemicals that treat building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, due to their habit of hunting at night their ears are more helpful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-location technique to identify insects and obstacles in the path they are traveling.
Bats are important to the NTS, which is responsible for the conservation of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 acres of land throughout the country.
It has trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, inspect nests and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation even established the first and only dedicated land reserve for bats in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Estate manager David Thompson says the estate is the best territory for them.
"Here in Threave we have a good place for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, a lot of veteran trees and all the nice habitats.
But there's still a lot we don't know about bats, so what we're doing here and on other properties can help us understand more about what they need to survive."
He stresses the importance of inspecting bats before performing maintenance on property because it is possible that the accidental destruction of at least one mother's nest could kill 400 women and young bats, potentially wiping out the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or destroy their nests.
Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust Elisabeth Ferrell is urging the public to help.
He said: "We have a lot to learn about our bats and we don't know the population status of many of our species."
